[1] China: Confirmation that 1st human case occurred in 2003
Date: Tue 8 Aug 2006
From: C Griot <griot@ivi.admin.ch>
Source: Associated Press report, Newsgroups: agen.ape.international [edited]
<news@presse1.admin.ch>

China on Tuesday [8 Aug 2006] confirmed
[officially] that a man died of avian influenza
in 2003, 2 years before the country reported its 1st human case of the disease.
A 24-year-old soldier became ill in November
2003, and the Health Ministry said in a statement
on its Web site that it has �confirmed the case as H5N1.
The death was first disclosed in June [2006] in a
letter by Chinese researchers to a U.S. medical
journal. It raised questions about whether China
failed to detect, or failed to report, an early human infection of bird flu.
The fatality came 2 years before China reported
its 1st bird flu death, but just a few months
before the virus tore through Viet Nam and Thailand.
--
Christian Griot
<Griot@ivi.admin.ch>
[See ProMED-mail post "Avian influenza, human
(90): China 20060629.1800" for an account of the
background to this report in the 22 Jun 2006
issue of the New England Journal of Medicine by a
group of independent Chinese research workers, of
a case of H5N1 avian influenza in a Chinese
patient dating back to 2003. It was treated with
some scepticism initially, particularly as the
original report was retracted by the authors, and
the retraction later withdrawn. The Chinese
Ministry of Health began a reinvestigation and
the above report indicates that the Chinese
authorities now accept the authenticity of the
original research and have now officially confirmed the results. - Mod.CP/JW]
