[5] Thailand: dengue diagnosis not confirmed
Date: Tue 8 Aug 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Bloomberg News Agency, Tue 8 Aug 2006 [edited]

[It was originally reported that a teenage boy
had tested positive for both avian influenza
virus and dengue virus infection; see ProMED-mail
post entitled, "Avian influenza, human (102):
Thailand, dengue exposure
20060726.2060". Reinvestigation has failed to
confirm the initial finding. - Mod.CP]
That the teenage boy who became Thailand's 1st
fatality from bird flu in 2006 wasn't also
infected with dengue hemorrhagic fever as
diagnosed, the Nation reported
[<http://etna.mcot.net/query.php?nid=23916>]
citing Public Health Minister Pinij Charusombat.
Results of laboratory tests released yesterday
showed no sign of dengue, the English-language daily newspaper reported.
Dengue, a potentially fatal mosquito-borne
infection endemic in Thailand, was initially
blamed for the youth's illness. The patient was
found to have the H5N1 avian influenza strain
after he died, and health officials said he might
have been infected with both viruses at the time of his death on 24 Jul 2006.
Thailand confirmed 2 deaths from H5N1 during the
past 2 weeks, taking the total number of human
infections reported in the Southeast nation to 24, of which 16 were fatal.
[Byline: Beth Jinks]
--
